Implement the private `locate/3` helper used by `search/2`.

`locate(node, prefix, acc)` walks down the trie from `node`, consuming `prefix`
one edge at a time. The `acc` argument is the actual path string spelled out from
the root down to `node` (it is built up as you descend so that, once the prefix is
fully consumed, you know the real string that reaches the landing node).

Behaviour:

- If `prefix` is `""`, the whole prefix has been consumed — return `{node, acc}`.
- Otherwise, take the first character of `prefix` as the edge key and look it up in
  `node.edges`:
  - If there is no matching edge, return `:nomatch`.
  - If there is an edge `%{label: label, child: child}`, decide by comparing
    `prefix` and `label`:
    - If `prefix` starts with `label`, the whole edge is consumed: recurse into
      `child` with the remainder of the prefix (drop `label`'s length) and `acc`
      extended by `label`.
    - Else if `label` starts with `prefix`, the prefix ends in the *middle* of this
      compressed edge: it still matches everything under `child`, so return
      `{child, acc <> label}` (the accumulated path is the full edge label, since
      every word below `child` carries that whole label).
    - Otherwise the prefix and label diverge — return `:nomatch`.

On success `locate/3` returns `{node_to_collect_from, path_to_that_node}`; on failure
it returns `:nomatch`. `search/2` then collects and sorts every terminal word under
the returned node.

